## Code Inspection

This issue appears to highlight a difference between GNU libc and FreeBSD libc.

The [manual page for pthread_cond_destroy on FreeBSD](https://man.freebsd.org/cgi/man.cgi?query=pthread_cond_destroy) states:

> The  pthread_cond_destroy() function frees the resources allocated by the condition variable cond.

However the [Linux manpage for pthread_cond_destroy](https://www.man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/pthread_cond_init.3.html) states that:

> In the LinuxThreads implementation, no resources are associated with condition variables, thus pthread_cond_destroy() actually does nothing except checking that the condition has no waiting threads.

There are only 2 source files that reference `pthread_cond_init`: [thread_posix.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/c53d7842726d0103696e03d79abd76539c65b101/crypto/thread/arch/thread_posix.c#L161) which already calls `pthread_cond_destroy` through `ossl_crypto_condvar_free` and [threads_pthread.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/c53d7842726d0103696e03d79abd76539c65b101/crypto/threads_pthread.c#L570) which has no references to `pthread_cond_destroy`.

Examining `threads_pthread.c` further, [pthread mutex and condition structures are initialized in ossl_rcu_lock_new](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/c53d7842726d0103696e03d79abd76539c65b101/crypto/threads_pthread.c#L589-L593) but are not destroyed in the [corresponding ossl_rcu_lock_free function](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/c53d7842726d0103696e03d79abd76539c65b101/crypto/threads_pthread.c#L604-L617).

Additionally, `pthread_cond_init` can fail and return an error code, which is not checked by the code in `ossl_rcu_lock_new`.

Both of these issues are addressed by the following patch which should apply cleanly to [commit c53d784272
](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/c53d7842726d0103696e03d79abd76539c65b101).

```diff
diff --git a/crypto/threads_pthread.c b/crypto/threads_pthread.c
index 75d26c9b30..2bfb5d3e1a 100644
--- a/crypto/threads_pthread.c
+++ b/crypto/threads_pthread.c
@@ -586,14 +586,49 @@ CRYPTO_RCU_LOCK *ossl_rcu_lock_new(int num_writers, OSSL_LIB_CTX *ctx)
         return NULL;

     new->ctx = ctx;
-    pthread_mutex_init(&new->write_lock, NULL);
-    pthread_mutex_init(&new->prior_lock, NULL);
-    pthread_mutex_init(&new->alloc_lock, NULL);
-    pthread_cond_init(&new->prior_signal, NULL);
-    pthread_cond_init(&new->alloc_signal, NULL);
+    if (pthread_mutex_init(&new->write_lock, NULL) != 0) {
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->write_lock);
+        OPENSSL_free(new);
+        return NULL;
+    }
+    if (pthread_mutex_init(&new->prior_lock, NULL) != 0) {
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->prior_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->write_lock);
+        OPENSSL_free(new);
+        return NULL;
+    }
+    if (pthread_mutex_init(&new->alloc_lock, NULL) != 0) {
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->alloc_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->prior_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->write_lock);
+        OPENSSL_free(new);
+        return NULL;
+    }
+    if (pthread_cond_init(&new->prior_signal, NULL) != 0) {
+        pthread_cond_destroy(&new->prior_signal);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->alloc_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->prior_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->write_lock);
+        OPENSSL_free(new);
+        return NULL;
+    }
+    if (pthread_cond_init(&new->alloc_signal, NULL) != 0) {
+        pthread_cond_destroy(&new->alloc_signal);
+        pthread_cond_destroy(&new->prior_signal);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->alloc_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->prior_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->write_lock);
+        OPENSSL_free(new);
+        return NULL;
+    }

     new->qp_group = allocate_new_qp_group(new, num_writers);
     if (new->qp_group == NULL) {
+        pthread_cond_destroy(&new->alloc_signal);
+        pthread_cond_destroy(&new->prior_signal);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->alloc_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->prior_lock);
+        pthread_mutex_destroy(&new->write_lock);
         OPENSSL_free(new);
         new = NULL;
     }
@@ -611,6 +646,12 @@ void ossl_rcu_lock_free(CRYPTO_RCU_LOCK *lock)
     /* make sure we're synchronized */
     ossl_synchronize_rcu(rlock);

+    pthread_cond_destroy(&lock->alloc_signal);
+    pthread_cond_destroy(&lock->prior_signal);
+    pthread_mutex_destroy(&lock->alloc_lock);
+    pthread_mutex_destroy(&lock->prior_lock);
+    pthread_mutex_destroy(&lock->write_lock);
+
     OPENSSL_free(rlock->qp_group);
     /* There should only be a single qp left now */
     OPENSSL_free(rlock);
```

## Summary

This is **not** a bug in OpenSSL itself. It is a bug in the upstream fuzz harness (`fuzz/provider.c`). Two functions — `do_evp_cipher` and `do_evp_md` — call parameter-setting functions before initializing the algorithm context, violating the EVP API contract. This makes ~20% of all fuzzer inputs (cipher + digest paths) produce no useful testing.

This is a similar class of fuzzer bug to #30278 (quic-server.c non-functional due to missing certificate setup).

## Fuzzer Location

- **File**: `fuzz/provider.c` in the [openssl/openssl](https://github.com/openssl/openssl) repository (upstream)
- **Fuzzer purpose**: Test EVP provider algorithms (ciphers, KDFs, MACs, etc.) with fuzz-generated parameters

## Bug Description

### do_evp_cipher: set_params before EncryptInit (dead code)

The original code calls `EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params(ctx, param)` **before** `EVP_EncryptInit_ex2(ctx, evp_cipher, key, iv, NULL)`. At this point, the cipher context has no algorithm associated with it.

```c
// Original code (WRONG ORDER):
ctx = EVP_CIPHER_CTX_new();
if (!EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params(ctx, param)) {  // ctx->cipher is NULL!
    EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);
    return 0;                                    // ALWAYS returns here
}
if (!EVP_EncryptInit_ex2(ctx, evp_cipher, key, iv, NULL)) {
    // Never reached
```

`EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params()` checks `ctx->cipher != NULL` internally. On a freshly created context with no cipher set, this check fails and returns 0. The function always early-returns, making the entire cipher path dead code.

This path is reached for `*operation % 10 == 1`, which is ~10% of all inputs.

### do_evp_md: set_params before DigestInit (dead code)

The identical bug exists in `do_evp_md`:

```c
// Original code (WRONG ORDER):
mdctx = EVP_MD_CTX_new();
if (!EVP_MD_CTX_set_params(mdctx, params)) {  // no digest algorithm set!
    // ALWAYS returns here
}
if (!EVP_DigestInit_ex2(mdctx, evp_md, NULL)) {
    // Never reached
```

This path is reached for `*operation % 10 == 0`, which is another ~10% of all inputs.

## Consequence

~20% of all fuzzer inputs hit dead code paths. The cipher and digest provider implementations are never actually tested. The fix revealed a genuine OpenSSL bug: `stack-buffer-overflow` in `DES_ede3_ofb64_encrypt` (ofb64ede.c:58), which was hidden by the dead code. (Details reported separately via the security reporting channel.)

## Coverage Comparison (1 minute, ASan, fork mode)

| Metric | Original | Fixed | Change |
|--------|----------|-------|--------|
| Edges | 1317 | 1994 | **+51.4%** |
| Features | 2100 | 2862 | **+36.3%** |
| Corpus | 92 | 128 | +39.1% |

## Fix

1. Swap `EVP_EncryptInit_ex2()` before `EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params()` in `do_evp_cipher`.
2. Swap `EVP_DigestInit_ex2()` before `EVP_MD_CTX_set_params()` in `do_evp_md`.
3. Heap-allocate key/IV buffers sized per-cipher (some ciphers like DES-EDE3-OFB retain internal pointers to the IV buffer).

```diff
 static int do_evp_cipher(const EVP_CIPHER *evp_cipher, const OSSL_PARAM param[])
 {
     ...
     ctx = EVP_CIPHER_CTX_new();
+    if (ctx == NULL)
+        return 0;

-    if (!EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params(ctx, param)) {
+    if (!EVP_EncryptInit_ex2(ctx, evp_cipher, key, iv, NULL)) {
+        EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);
+        return 0;
+    }
+
+    if (!EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params(ctx, param)) {
         EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);
         return 0;
     }

-    if (!EVP_EncryptInit_ex2(ctx, evp_cipher, key, iv, NULL)) {
-        EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);
-        return 0;
-    }
     if (!EVP_EncryptUpdate(ctx, outbuf, &outlen, ...)) {
```

Same pattern for `do_evp_md`:

```diff
-    if (!EVP_MD_CTX_set_params(mdctx, params)) {
+    if (!EVP_DigestInit_ex2(mdctx, evp_md, NULL)) {
+        r = 0;
+        goto end;
+    }
+
+    if (!EVP_MD_CTX_set_params(mdctx, params)) {
         r = 0;
         goto end;
     }
-    if (!EVP_DigestInit_ex2(mdctx, evp_md, NULL)) {
-        r = 0;
-        goto end;
-    }
```

## Summary

A stack buffer over-read exists in OpenSSL's DES OFB64 and CFB64 encryption functions. The `num` parameter (tracking the byte offset within the current 8-byte block) can be set to an arbitrary value via `EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params()` without range validation. When `num >= 8`, the first loop iteration in `DES_ede3_ofb64_encrypt` reads past the end of a stack-local `DES_cblock d[8]` buffer. Leaked stack data is XOR'd into the ciphertext output.

**Affected functions** (all in `crypto/des/`):
- `DES_ede3_ofb64_encrypt` (ofb64ede.c)
- `DES_ede3_cfb64_encrypt` (cfb64ede.c)
- `DES_ofb64_encrypt` (ofb64enc.c)
- `DES_cfb64_encrypt` (cfb64enc.c)

**Impact**: Stack data leak into ciphertext (information disclosure). Read-only overflow, not exploitable for code execution.

**Severity**: Low. Requires the application to pass attacker-controlled params to `EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params`, which is uncommon. DES/3DES is deprecated.

---

## Root Cause Analysis

### 1. Missing validation in `ossl_cipher_common_set_ctx_params`

`providers/implementations/ciphers/ciphercommon.c:646-654`:

```c
if (p->num != NULL) {
    unsigned int num;

    if (!OSSL_PARAM_get_uint(p->num, &num)) {
        ERR_raise(ERR_LIB_PROV, PROV_R_FAILED_TO_GET_PARAMETER);
        return 0;
    }
    ctx->num = num;  // No range check! Accepts any unsigned int.
}
```

The `num` parameter represents the byte offset within the current cipher block. For DES (8-byte block), valid range is `[0, 7]`. No validation is performed.

### 2. Unmasked first use in `DES_ede3_ofb64_encrypt`

`crypto/des/ofb64ede.c:27-59`:

```c
void DES_ede3_ofb64_encrypt(... int *num)
{
    register int n = *num;    // Line 29: reads num directly, NO masking
    DES_cblock d;             // Line 31: 8 bytes on stack
    ...
    while (l--) {
        if (n == 0) {
            // regenerate keystream into d[0..7]
        }
        *(out++) = *(in++) ^ d[n];   // Line 58: OOB read when n >= 8
        n = (n + 1) & 0x07;          // Line 59: masked only AFTER the read
    }
}
```

The masking `& 0x07` at line 59 only applies **after** the first read. On the first iteration with `n >= 8`, `d[n]` reads past the 8-byte stack buffer.

### 3. Call chain

```
EVP_CIPHER_CTX_set_params(ctx, params)
  → ossl_cipher_generic_set_ctx_params()
    → ossl_cipher_common_set_ctx_params()
      → ctx->num = num;               // arbitrary value, no check

EVP_EncryptUpdate(ctx, out, &outlen, in, inl)
  → ossl_cipher_generic_stream_update()
    → ossl_cipher_hw_tdes_ofb(ctx, ...)
      → int num = ctx->num;           // reads unchecked value
      → DES_ede3_ofb64_encrypt(..., &num)
        → d[num]                       // STACK OOB READ
```

